segments.text: finishes.
Okay, well, anyway, I was fortunate enough to be one of the winners.
There were three winners.
Once they had the highest grade on these exams.
And the other two winners were an individual named JW Collier.
And the other was an Hispanic, Gus Pena, P-E-N-A.
So the three of us were to go on this tour.
And Professor Mogford, the cotton expert, had been taking the tour every time for the last several years.
I think either he or maybe it was his wife getting tired of him being gone all summer.
So they elected Dr. Trotter to go, the head of the department.
So Dr. Trotter took the three of us on this tour.
And I'll go over it briefly.
We spent about three weeks in the United States traveling in a car, Dr. Trotter's car.
There were four of us in the car and all our luggage.

We left College Station and went across the southeast through Louisiana, Alabama, and so forth, stopping at experiment stations on the way, and supposedly, anyway, studying cotton and our other local matters.
But we got all the way over to the east coast and then went up the east coast to...

through Virginia and then up to Washington, D.C., and spent two or three days in Washington with some of the federal people there interested, ran the cotton programs, and then went up to New York for two or three days and went to the cotton exchange, I guess it was.
There where they marketed the cotton and visited some of the people there and
generally had a great time and we had some entertainment.
I'm sure we went to one or two shows.
I guess we went to the Rockettes at Rockefeller Center.
So that was, this was big for all of us.
We, the students, we hadn't hardly been out of the state, I guess, at that time.
Well, no, I'd been out, but not to any extent.
This, certainly never been to the East Coast before.
So it was a great occasion.
The part in this country was great.
Then we got on a ship, and it was a converted merchant ship.
During the summer, these shipping lines would refit some of their transport ships to carry passengers during the summer.
We had about 100 people on there, and it was all one class.
And it was just great.
Everybody was friendly and there were plenty of girls on board.
There were a lot of them teachers or high school, excuse me, college students.
And they were all all over the country.
So it was, the voyage was really quite interesting.
We left New York and landed at,
What's the port in England?
Liverpool.
Liverpool, yeah.
I kept saying Manchester, Birmingham.
I knew when he landed at Liverpool.
It was about a 10-day trip.
It was not a fast ship, as you might expect, something like that.
But it was really an enjoyable occasion.
Then we spent about three or four weeks in England and on the continent going around.
through the cotton mills and cotton exchanges, anything, dealing with cotton and some entertainment off and on.
Well, we got off at Liverpool and then went to Manchester, which is the main mill town, and to London, and went across the English Channel from Dover to Calais.
No, we landed in Belgium.
What would that have been?
I can't think of, Austin, Austin, Belgium.
That was a few hour trip, as I recall.
And then went some meals in Belgium, then to Germany.
We made a trip down the Rhine one day, which really was informative, interesting.
Did you see, the German part of the trip, did you see any evidences of Nazism?
I want to tell you this, and it's easy to say in retrospect, but you would have had to have been blind, deaf, and dumb not to know that the Nazis were getting ready for something.
They were just troops marching, not marching, just everywhere, moving here, moving there, and this was the summer of 1938.
Well, I paid attention to it, but I wasn't in a position really evaluating it, but it was just,
Why in the world would they have all these troops around if they were going to do something?
And what was next year that they marched into Poland?
But they were all busy and active and moving.
And the ships were up and down the Rhine were loaded with coal, iron, various resources.
And it sure looked obvious that something was going to take place there.
And, yeah, there were the Browns.

suited fellows with the swastika on their sleeves one thing that surprised me is that on this ride down the rhine that day half the germans on there or more seemed they could speak enough english you could communicate with them and i remember visiting with two or three different germans one of them was a girl there who was i guess she was in college somewhere but she could talk
English quite well.
Mainly talked about where she was going to school, what she was doing, something about the country.
We spent altogether two or three days there in Germany and went down the Rhine and I believe we got off at Mainz.
I think we got on at Cologne and off at Mainz and went into Switzerland.
That wasn't much cotton tour in Switzerland, but Switzerland's a beautiful place to see.
We went to Lake Lucerne, I guess it was.
This is all kind of amazing for...
small town people who hadn't been anywhere at age 21.
From a few days in Switzerland, we went on to France and Paris for a few days and saw the Folies Bougier for the first time.
So this wasn't all work.
Then we went across France to tours, I believe.
And then on to Laharve.
I was trying to think of the port where we departed from.
I couldn't think for the moment, but got on the ship coming back at Laharve.
And for some reason, they mixed up our tickets or changed their shipping schedules.
And we were given first-class accommodations
on this ship.
It was a regular class ship.
It was a big ship with several hundred people, pastors on board.
And to show you how limited my background was, it was one of the worst experiences I've ever had.
I didn't fit in.
We didn't fit in with these people.
That didn't really happen.
These were
Most of them wealthy people, and they had their own cliques and their own practices, and we just felt outside of it to some extent.
Oh, it was all right, but you could really tell the difference.
You toured cotton mills in Europe.
Right.
Did you tour any cotton mills in New England?
No.
I don't know whether there were any left by then.
Did you tour any American mills?
Oh, yes.
Now I'm recalling a little better.
I think the shift had primarily occurred from New England mills to the southern mills, and we went through two or three large ones in North Carolina and Georgia in that area.
Yeah, I failed to mention that as we went through there.
How long was this whole trip?
Six months?
No, no, just the summer, 10 to 12 weeks, something like that.
We left right after school was out.
Let's back up just a little now.
As we're getting ready for you to graduate, that little doodad fell off, and it's there in the chair.
No worries.
No worries.
Okay, it's still recording.
As you approached commissioning and...
commencement and so forth.
Do you remember those events for you?
What was commissioning and commencement like?
Well, see, I wasn't eligible for a commission, so I wasn't involved with that.
I did take the two years required basic military science, so I was not in on commissioning.
What about graduation?
Well, we had final review.
I remember that and marched in it and graduated.
Commencement was, I believe I'm correct on this, held in Kyle Field.
I can't remember the speaker.
I don't remember who he was.
I remember I was going with Margaret then and she was up for it and my parents and so forth.
What kind of life did you think you were getting ready to
What do you think you were going to be doing in the next few years?
Well, when I started school at A&M, this shows a limitation in my vision, I guess, but I was going back to Arkansas into agriculture in some form, shape, form, or fashion.
But at commencement, I had not...
made arrangements to get into graduate school yet, and I've forgotten just what the status of that was.
I believe I'd initiated some activity there during the spring to look into the assistantship over in the Experiment Station.
little Jocko Roberts, probably.
And he was the student on this assistantship at that time.
So I remember going over to talk to him some about it in the spring of 38.
So by commencement time, I had some concept perhaps of continuing
at A&M there in graduate school and working in the experiment station for at least the next step, so I wasn't thinking too much.
I had marriage on my mind more than anything else probably right about then.
Well, it was small enough that it didn't seem to be a big financial factor.
I don't know that I can remember specifically, but I've on several different occasions anywhere had people recognize it and

call attention to it and and in my case particularly there's a lot of interest generated in it when they see it they begin to wonder well it's practically smooth when that guy get out he might he ought to be gone by now i did lose it one time here this was since we moved back here one time a few years ago for about a month and uh
The lady that cleans up every couple of weeks for it happened to locate it one day on the floor in a corner somewhere.
So I've been ever grateful to her for it.
Do you remember going to Aggie Muster as an undergraduate?
April 21st, Muster.
I can't recall that.
Were they being held?
Well, you're confirming what I have encountered in others.
Most people don't remember musters until after World War II.
And I have the impression that World War II made a great change in mustard and in bonfire, that those traditions became more important here.
And more attention given to... Well, that...
I'm groping for that muster experience, but I can't remember it as a student or even in graduate school right after that.
Shirley Cain.
All right, let's see.
Back to your student days.
There must have been a variety of students.
As far as you recall, how were Hispanic American students treated?
We had, again, based on my memory, one Hispanic student in our battery, and he was emulated almost.
He was treated with extreme respect and regard and was just an outstanding individual.
You may know this family, Reyes.
I would think they've had five or six children.
Children go through A&M, and what was, I can't think of this one's first name.
I can visualize him, but he was, I think, a year behind me, and just a wonderful person.

And last year I was here, his brother came in as a freshman, and then I knew another, one of the brothers that worked for the Experiment Station down in Beeville for years and years, and was just outstanding.
Did you know any of the Japanese Americans?
I can't remember the fellow's name, but I'm sure he's recorded somewhere in the NMN.
He was probably a class of 37, maybe.
Was this Kishi from over at Orange Field?
The name didn't... What about Jewish students?
Did you know any Jewish students?
You bet.
Well, I thought like I knew a hundred of them, but I knew one that was a scream.
You know about this Japanese, I can't recall that fellow's name.
He was an outstanding student here in the 36th, 7th, 8th, along in there.
And I remember there was discussion about him among those of us who had known him.

after the war started and what happened to him and where he was and did he go back to Japan and all that and I can't recall it but he was a stellar student and well known on the campus and I think perhaps in the core ranks
Anyway, that was the only Japanese student I remember.
Jewish students, there was a whole flock of them from New York or New Jersey or somewhere in the northeast going to vet school because they didn't have any vet schools up there.
So all of them that could get in, I guess, they were coming here.
So that was one source of Jewish students that I
can't actually recall one of their names offhand.
I remember seeing them.
And were those students treated just about like everybody else was?
I think there might have been some, not severe resentment, but they were referred to as a group.
The out-of-state ones?
Yeah, the out-of-state ones that had come down here to go to Beth's school.
What about the Jewish students from Houston?
Oh, well, I only know one of them real well, and his name was Ike Wexler.
And there was a Wexler jewelry store in Houston, and that's where he came from.
He was one of the funniest guys.
Everything was a big joke to him.
He was a heavyset fellow, loved to eat and have a good time, and life was just one big party to him.
And I don't know whether, I doubt if he ever graduated, but everybody...
I just liked him.
I think he was in there in our outfit I was in or the one next in the dormitory right nearby.
But I don't remember any, certainly wasn't any significance attached to him.
In fact, he'd laugh about being a Jew.
It was a big joke.
Am I correct that in that era,
Where you came from, where you worshiped or didn't worship, your ancestry didn't matter.
You were an Agate.
That was the key thing.
I'd say that's a reasonable statement.
Individuals were liked, disliked, or whatever, based on their particular characteristics.
Now, scholars weren't especially...
I don't know that they were dishonored, but that wasn't one of the characteristics that made a student popular or unpopular.
And I suppose there was a little reaction to the perfect student, the one who followed all the rules and marched just right and was rewarded, usually with a military ranking.
I didn't touch on that much, but the military ranking
aspects of the Corps was quite significant.
You know, who was company commander, who was the major and the lieutenant colonel, and certainly the cadet colonel was a tremendously important position.
In terms of status, was the cadet colonel the highest in terms of student status?
Recognition.
Was that the highest recognition that a student could have?
That would be my recollection.
Did you all even have a student body president that you knew about?
I don't recall one.
The military ranking was a life and death matter in a way.
It was the crux of the whole Corps at that time and really the most,
rewarding position was a unit commander, or at least that's what I've observed and been told, that you had a company of people you were responsible for, and you were.

I mean, they took responsibility, and of course they had a top kick, the sergeant, the junior, and the officers of positions, military positions above them, the majors, these lieutenant colonels, they were staff people, and they didn't really have
They had jurisdiction, you might say, over four companies, but not over individuals.
But the company commander was where the real jurisdiction came.
And it affected the quality of the organization dramatically.
Because some companies, you'd have an outstanding company commander.
The students in there would be passing their courses.
And if somebody got behind, they got some help, either a
Either physical or metal or both.
Yeah.
Okay.
You graduated, were away for a little while, and then you came back to A&M.
as a member of the staff?
No, I was just a graduate student at that time.
We finished the cotton tour right about the end of the summer.

And I was starting graduate school in September and to start on this assistant, what they called an assistantship at the time, in the experiment station in the agronomy part of the experiment station, which I
At that time, Experiment Station was a separate entity from the college teaching part of the school and operated more or less independently.
But there were graduate students throughout the Experiment Station that worked there and took the courses at the college, which it was called at that time.
And that, then World War II, and then
After the war, when do you return to A&M?
Well, I came back in, let's see, I guess it was the beginning of 46.
Do you want anything about the 38?
Let's jump on to when you joined the professional staff here.
After the war.
Let's see.
Well, I guess I went on the staff in 1940, actually, when I finished my degree, finished my master's degree in the summer of 1940.
And Dr. Mangelsdorf left at that time, resigned from the Experiment Station and accepted a position as professor at Harvard, which is where he had gone for his graduate degree.
So I was a mere graduate student of 23, I think, if I remember right, in 1940.
And he left without a whole lot of notice, and obtaining replacements was becoming somewhat difficult at that time.
The war wasn't far away, and there
The military was already becoming active, so I was there on hand, and I was just asked to take over the program.
This was an experiment station, what was called the Corn Improvement Program.
So Dr. Mangelsdorf left, and I took over the program in 1940.
a greatly underqualified member of the staff, you could say, at that time.
And I think it was on somewhat of a temporary basis.
I remember I was paid $200 a month, though, which was fantastic because I had married in 1938, soon after graduate school.
I mean, soon after I graduated.
And then my wife worked.
most of the time while I was in graduate school.
But then I could support the families somewhat on $200 a month.
I have one story I wanted to mention, if it's agreeable to you, about my most embarrassing moment that occurred.
I guess this was while I was in graduate school.
I think I've told you a little bit previously about the cotton tour and coming back from that.
And we were married on September 30th in 1938.
So I was basically married the whole time I was going to graduate school.
And sometime in the fall of 38, I still was active in the agronomy department.
And they were having an agronomy society meeting one night.
And they invited myself and I think it was one or two others
individuals who'd been on that cotton tour, previous ones anyway.
The program was a cotton tour.
So I took my wife.
There were several women, faculty wives or so forth there at the meeting.
It was kind of a social event as well as a meeting.
And I was one of those giving a brief report of the cotton tour, what I thought about it and appreciated it and so forth.
And I don't know.
My mind must have been out of gear at the moment anyway.
I was telling how much I appreciated the cotton to her and how enjoyable it had been and something I'd remember all my life.
And then I looked down at my bride and said, in fact, I enjoyed it more than anything I've ever done.
And I kind of looked at her and said, until I got married.
That brought down the house.
I still remember that.
It was great.
Fortunately, they had a film they were showing, so somebody turned off the lights like that.
Kind of took the brunt off of it, but I've always remembered that faux pas.
Anyway, you can imagine a room full of Aggies with a combat like that.
Anyway.
So you were on the staff until the war, and during the war.
Well, I started on the staff in 1940 and took over the corn improvement project.
And this was important, not just to me, but from the standpoint of the Experiment Station.
The corn grown throughout the United States had been bridal corn up to that time.
And of course, Texas, the South, was behind the Midwest in the adoption of hybrid corn.
So Dr. Mangelfeld initiated the program to start hybrid corn for Texas.
had not reached fruition.
There was none being grown in 1940.
But it was right at a point where we could introduce it and get it started.
So it was a pretty important period right then as far as development of hybrids and the introduction into the Texas market.
And that was the main thing that I was responsible for during the 40s there.
And I worked
Spent a lot of my time working with seed growers throughout the state that just started producing hybrid corn and making it available.
What were the important steps in that program's success, as you look back on it now?
Well, are you familiar with the procedure for developing hybrid corn?
Or should I outline it and just do it briefly?
Well.
Hybrid corn is basically developed through the initial creation of inbred lines, and these are obtained by inbreeding a variety of corn.
Dr. Mangelsdorf had taken some of the local varieties that were adapted to Texas here and had inbred them, that is, self-pollinate them generation after generation.

develop inbred line from that were adapted to texas you couldn't just import corn from the midwest and put it down here it wasn't adapted so he had developed some lines adapted to texas and we were just in the process of hybridizing these lines to produce hybrid corn and to identify those that produced the best hybrids and this process continued on through the early 40s and we started
introducing hybrids in 41, 42, in the early 40 period there and worked with the seed growers.
It was a good deal of time and effort expanded in the program throughout the state at that time.
Where geographically in Texas, where was the biggest concentration of the early hybrid crops?
I'd say in the Blackland area.
In 1940, there were five
believe it or not, five million acres of corn and the average yield was 15 bushels per acre.
Hardly worth growing.
And there was a lot of corn through the Blackland area and even on East Texas and the Gulf Coast and on even down toward Beville and that area there.
Well, most of the state except the, you got west of, say, Lyon, Austin to Wichita Falls and out west where the rainfall was low.
Five million acres representing quite important acres throughout the state.
And I'd like to get this in there somewhere, and let me do it now if I may.
One of my important experiences was in working in the corn improvement program.
We utilized the experiment substation in Texas.
You're probably familiar with some of them.
But at that time, they were located at West Lakeland Valley and Beeville in the South of San Antonio area, Beaumont over in East Texas, Temple in the Black Land.
That was an important location for us in the corn program.
We even had one in Nacogdoches over in East Texas.
As an interesting aside, it was set up in 1911, I think, for tobacco improvement.
